JavaScript Day 3 – Control Statements ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Control statements help JavaScript make decisions.

For example:

If the user is logged in → Show Dashboard.
If the password is incorrect → Show Error.
If marks are above 40 → Pass.

Today we'll learn:

if
if...else
else if
switch
1. if Statement ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

The if statement executes code only if the condition is true.

Syntax
if (condition) {
    // code to execute
}
Example
let age = 20;

if (age >= 18) {
    console.log("You can vote");
}
Output
You can vote

Since 20 >= 18 is true, the code inside the if block runs.

Example 2
let age = 15;

if (age >= 18) {
    console.log("Eligible");
}
Output
(No Output)

The condition is false, so nothing is printed.

2. if...else ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Use if...else when you want one block of code to run if the condition is true, and another block if it's false.

Syntax
if (condition) {
    // true block
} else {
    // false block
}
Example
let age = 16;

if (age >= 18) {
    console.log("Eligible to Vote");
} else {
    console.log("Not Eligible");
}
Output
Not Eligible
Example 2
let password = "admin123";

if (password === "admin123") {
    console.log("Login Successful");
} else {
    console.log("Invalid Password");
}
Output
Login Successful
3. else if ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Used when there are multiple conditions.

Syntax
if (condition1) {

} else if (condition2) {

} else if (condition3) {

} else {

}
Example: Student Grade
let marks = 85;

if (marks >= 90) {
    console.log("Grade A+");
} else if (marks >= 75) {
    console.log("Grade A");
} else if (marks >= 60) {
    console.log("Grade B");
} else if (marks >= 40) {
    console.log("Grade C");
} else {
    console.log("Fail");
}
Output
Grade A
Example: Traffic Signal
let signal = "Green";

if (signal === "Red") {
    console.log("Stop");
} else if (signal === "Yellow") {
    console.log("Get Ready");
} else if (signal === "Green") {
    console.log("Go");
} else {
    console.log("Invalid Signal");
}
Output
Go
Nested if

You can place an if inside another if.

Example
let age = 25;
let hasLicense = true;

if (age >= 18) {

    if (hasLicense) {
        console.log("You can drive");
    } else {
        console.log("License Required");
    }

} else {
    console.log("Too Young");
}
Output
You can drive
4. switch Statement ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Used when comparing one variable against multiple values.

Syntax
switch (expression) {

    case value1:
        // code
        break;

    case value2:
        // code
        break;

    default:
        // code
}
Example
let day = 3;

switch (day) {

    case 1:
        console.log("Monday");
        break;

    case 2:
        console.log("Tuesday");
        break;

    case 3:
        console.log("Wednesday");
        break;

    case 4:
        console.log("Thursday");
        break;

    default:
        console.log("Invalid Day");
}
Output
Wednesday
Why is break Important?

Without break, JavaScript continues executing the following cases.

Example
let day = 2;

switch (day) {

    case 1:
        console.log("Monday");

    case 2:
        console.log("Tuesday");

    case 3:
        console.log("Wednesday");

    default:
        console.log("Done");
}
Output
Tuesday
Wednesday
Done

This is called fall-through.

Correct Example
let day = 2;

switch (day) {

    case 1:
        console.log("Monday");
        break;

    case 2:
        console.log("Tuesday");
        break;

    case 3:
        console.log("Wednesday");
        break;

    default:
        console.log("Invalid");
}
Output
Tuesday
switch with Strings
let color = "blue";

switch (color) {

    case "red":
        console.log("Stop");
        break;

    case "green":
        console.log("Go");
        break;

    case "blue":
        console.log("Ocean");
        break;

    default:
        console.log("Unknown Color");
}
Output
Ocean
if vs switch
if...else	switch
Works with any condition	Best for checking one variable against many values
Can use <, >, <=, >=	Checks exact matches (===)
More flexible	Cleaner for multiple fixed values
Real-World Examples
Example 1: ATM Withdrawal
let balance = 5000;
let amount = 3000;

if (amount <= balance) {
    console.log("Withdrawal Successful");
} else {
    console.log("Insufficient Balance");
}
Output
Withdrawal Successful
Example 2: Login System
let username = "admin";
let password = "12345";

if (username === "admin" && password === "12345") {
    console.log("Login Successful");
} else {
    console.log("Invalid Credentials");
}
Example 3: Even or Odd
let number = 18;

if (number % 2 === 0) {
    console.log("Even");
} else {
    console.log("Odd");
}
Output
Even
Interview Questions ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
1. What is the difference between if and if...else?
if executes code only when the condition is true.
if...else executes one block when true and another when false.
2. When should you use switch instead of if...else?

Use switch when comparing a single variable against many fixed values.

3. Why is break used in a switch statement?

It stops execution after the matching case. Without it, execution continues into the next cases (fall-through).

4. Can you use comparison operators like > inside a switch case?

No. switch compares values using strict equality (===). For range checks like >, <, or >=, use if...else.

Common Mistakes
❌ Using = instead of ===
if (age = 18) {
    console.log("Wrong");
}

This assigns 18 to age instead of comparing it.

✅ Correct
if (age === 18) {
    console.log("Correct");
}
❌ Forgetting break
switch(day) {
    case 1:
        console.log("Monday");
}

Always use break unless you intentionally want fall-through.
